<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-967-020  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 967 020.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Dec 11 1989 n345 p57(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>LANs: getting larger? (local area networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zarley, Craig.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Despite the possibilities that Microsoft's LAN Manager 2.0 andCompaq Computer's Systempro hold with regard to single-server LANssupporting hundreds of microcomputers, there is still somequestion as to whether anyone will really need or want such alarge network.andP;  In fact, according to International Data Corp, theway people work, rather than the performance of sophisticatedhardware and software, conspires against node proliferation onsingle-server LANs.andP;  Such networks, those exceeding 100workstations, represent only five percent of all single-serverLANs, the company has found, while nodes on the averagesingle-server LAN average 12 to 14.andP;  Moreover, larger LANs oftendo not make sense regardless of the server's power if the LAN isnot connected with a fiber-optic backbone.andP;  Still, the advent of80486-based, dual-processor servers will continue to tempt someLAN administrators into consolidating small individual LANs intolarger networks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   LAN Manager 2.0 (Network management software) (usage)Compaq SystemPro (File server) (usage).andO;Topic:     Local Area NetworksUser NeedsSizeApplicationsIndustry Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>